For global data like time, these can be traits added to the world. **World traits do not appear in queries.**", "newString": "### Deferred commands

Mutating entities while iterating a query can disturb the results being iterated. `world.deferred` batches mutations into a command buffer that is applied later, keeping iteration stable.

```js
world.query(Position, Health).updateEach(([position, health], entity) => {
  if (health.value <= 0) {
    // Instead of destroying immediately, defer it.
    world.deferred.destroy(entity)
  }
})
// Deferred commands are flushed automatically when updateEach exits.
```

The buffer supports `spawn`, `destroy`, `add`, `remove`, `addExclusive` and `flush`.

```js
// spawn returns an entity handle you can reference right away
const bullet = world.deferred.spawn(Position({ x: 0, y: 0 }), Velocity)
world.deferred.add(bullet, IsActive)
world.deferred.remove(player, Shield)

// addExclusive replaces every existing pair of a relation with a single one
world.deferred.addExclusive(unit, Targeting(enemy))
// a wildcard target clears all of a relation's pairs
world.deferred.addExclusive(unit, Targeting('*'))
```

Key behaviors:

- Commands execute in the order they were deferred; later values for the same trait replace earlier ones.
- `has` and `get` on an entity return the state it will have _after_ flush, even before the buffer is applied.
- Pending commands are flushed when an `updateEach` loop exits, when `world.deferred.flush()` is called, or when a non-deferred mutation touches an entity with pending commands. Nested `updateEach` loops flush their own buffer independently, preserving any outer buffer.
- Commands targeting a destroyed entity are silently skipped, and spawning then destroying the same entity in one buffer cancels out. Add/remove subscriptions fire once per pair based on the difference between the state before and after the flush.

